article.description: The Indiana Pacers thought they were in for a tougher game than they got from the New Orleans Hornets, who had won three straig
article.headline: New Orleans falls to 0-3 against Indiana
article.linkText: Hornets can't shoot straight in home loss to Pacers
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers thought they were in for a tougher game than they got from the New Orleans Hornets, who had won three straight coming in and wanted to prove they could play with the Eastern Conference leaders.
 
O'Neal
Instead, the Pacers pulled away in the middle of the second quarter and never came close to losing the lead again in an 83-72 victory Wednesday night. "Being number one in our division, we have a bigger target on our back,'' said Jermaine O'Neal, who turned his left ankle early but came back to score 14 points and grab nine rebounds for the Pacers. "We just wanted to kind of come out and jab, jab, jab and then hopefully take over in the fourth quarter, but we were able to take control right away." Brad Miller scored 18 points and Reggie Miller added 17 for Indiana, which never trailed after taking a 6-5 lead on Reggie Miller's open layup off a baseline cut. Ron Artest finished with 11 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists as the Pacers improved to 13-12 on the road. "When you have a team like this and you get (points) from all different ways, it makes your team all that much more dangerous," Reggie Miller said. "I think that's how we're keeping teams off balance." Poor shooting from the field and foul line plagued New Orleans, which tied a season low for points. The Hornets, now 0-3 against Indiana with one meeting left next month, finished shooting just under 33 percent. "The thing I'm pleased about tonight is we were able to win with a different style," Pacers coach Isiah Thomas said. "We can play up-tempo, we can play halfcourt and we can grind it out." Thomas said Artest's timing seems a bit off on offense, in part because he served a four-game suspension just before the All-Star break, but his defense remains strong. "I don't know if I've seen a defender like him who can go out every single night and accept that challenge and still play all areas of the game," Thomas said. "Normally, you have a defensive player and that's his job. With Artest, the whole season he'll take the top scorer and then he'll play on the offensive side of the ball, too." Artest guarded Jamal Mashburn, who led New Orleans with 18 points but was only 7-of-22 from the field. P.J. Brown added 14 points. Jamaal Magloire grabbed a career-high 20 rebounds, although he had more opportunities than usual on the offensive end -- where he pulled down eight -- with the Hornets missing so many shots. Magloire also scored 13 but shot only 3-of-13. New Orleans went 15-of-25 from the foul line, where Indiana was 24-of-31. The Hornets were 3-of-13 from 3-point range, one night after going 1-for-9 in a victory at Miami. Hornets coach Paul Silas felt his club's cold shooting wasted what was otherwise a good effort. "You can't hold Indiana to 83 points and not play well," Silas said. "When you are not making shots, everything looks dismal, but all in all, I was very happy with our effort." Indiana shot a relatively low 40.3 percent in what was an all-around ugly game. But the Pacers were able to get the ball inside, where they outscored New Orleans 34-22. "Everybody played good team defense and that's what won the game, because we played horrible offense," Artest said. New Orleans used a 7-1 run to cut Indiana's lead to 48-40. Mashburn scored all seven points, hitting a 3-pointer, converting a steal into an end-to-end layup and then hitting another short basket on a drive. But Indiana then went on a 12-3 run that included jumpers by Brad Miller and Reggie Miller and a dunk by O'Neal. Brad Miller's seventh field goal in nine attempts made the score 60-43 with 3:01 left in the period, and Indiana led 65-49 to start the fourth. Game notes
Artest ripped a courtside microphone from the tape holding it on the press table after being called for a meaningless foul at the end of the game. Artest was playing only his second game after serving a four-game suspension for an altercation with Miami Heat coach Pat Riley and making an obscene gesture during that game. ... With a pair of free throws in the second quarter, Reggie Miller passed Elgin Baylor for 17th on the NBA's career scoring list. Miller now has 23,158 career points in regular season games. ... Rap star Mystikal performed at halftime. Also on hand, sitting courtside, were Indianapolis Colts quarterback Peyton Manning, and chef Emeril Lagasse, who has three restaurants in town.
